02:10:43,275 --> 02:10:45,821
That's right, but the Communist
at home have never been traitors.

1598
02:11:11,434 --> 02:11:14,103
- Communist!
- Socialist!

1599
02:11:22,280 --> 02:11:25,700
<i>Capitaine,  good night.
He was a Socialist, you know.</i>

1600
02:11:25,825 --> 02:11:29,955
We can stay. I know
that we can stay. We can.

1601
02:11:33,501 --> 02:11:36,880
You know, we always
helped the people.

1602
02:11:37,005 --> 02:11:38,924
We work with the people.

1603
02:11:40,009 --> 02:11:43,262
So we can be friends,
we are agreed.

1604
02:11:55,319 --> 02:11:59,239
See, Captain,
when my grandfather...

1605
02:12:00,992 --> 02:12:03,912
and my uncle's father
came here...

1606
02:12:05,872 --> 02:12:08,501
there was nothing...
nothing.

1607
02:12:09,627 --> 02:12:12,296
The Vietnamese were nothing.

1608
02:12:14,049 --> 02:12:16,384
So we worked hard...

1609
02:12:16,510 --> 02:12:18,429
very hard, and brought...

1610
02:12:18,554 --> 02:12:22,141
the rubber from Brazil,
and then plant it here.

1611
02:12:23,351 --> 02:12:26,480
We took the Vietnamese,
work with them...

1612
02:12:27,356 --> 02:12:29,233
make something...

1613
02:12:29,358 --> 02:12:32,070
something out of nothing.

1614
02:12:32,195 --> 02:12:36,617
So when you ask me why
we want to stay here, Captain...

1615
02:12:38,202 --> 02:12:42,290
we want to stay here because
it's ours... it belongs to us.

1616
02:12:42,416 --> 02:12:44,334
It keeps our family together.

1617
02:12:46,211 --> 02:12:48,131
I mean, we fight for that.

1618
02:12:50,216 --> 02:12:54,555
While you Americans,
you are fighting for...

1619
02:12:54,680 --> 02:12:58,642
the biggest nothing in history.

1620
02:13:05,860 --> 02:13:10,698
I'm sorry, Captain. I will see
if your men need any help to...

1621
02:13:10,823 --> 02:13:12,909
repair your boat...

1622
02:13:13,034 --> 02:13:16,037
so that you can go on
with your war.

1623
02:13:51,747 --> 02:13:54,625
I apologise
for my family, Captain.

1624
02:13:56,210 --> 02:13:58,505
We have all lost much here.

1625
02:13:59,756 --> 02:14:02,550
Hubert... his wife
and two sons.

1626
02:14:07,431 --> 02:14:09,643
And I have lost a husband.

1627
02:14:15,483 --> 02:14:17,235
I understand.

1628
02:14:17,360 --> 02:14:19,904
You are tired of the war.

1629
02:14:21,573 --> 02:14:24,118
I can see it in your face.

1630
02:14:26,161 --> 02:14:30,208
'Twas the same in the eyes
of the soldiers of our war.

1631
02:14:31,668 --> 02:14:35,381
<i>We called them
"Les Soldats Perdus..."</i>

1632
02:14:35,506 --> 02:14:37,716
The Lost Soldiers.

1633
02:14:42,431 --> 02:14:44,976
If you like,
we can have some cognac.

1634
02:14:52,151 --> 02:14:55,237
I have to...
to see about my men and...

1635
02:15:02,496 --> 02:15:05,374
The war will be
still here tomorrow.

1636
02:15:15,636 --> 02:15:17,847
Yeah, I guess you're right.

1637
02:15:25,899 --> 02:15:28,651
I noticed you had
no wine at dinner.

1638
02:15:29,736 --> 02:15:32,865
No, I don't drink wine.

1639
02:15:35,910 --> 02:15:39,998
I do like cognac, but I don't want
any now. Thank you.

1640
02:15:41,291 --> 02:15:43,711
Well...

1641
02:15:43,836 --> 02:15:46,881
then I...
I must drink alone.

1642
02:15:57,143 --> 02:16:00,356
Will you go back
after the war to America?

1643
02:16:06,029 --> 02:16:09,491
Then you're like us...
your home is here.

1644
02:16:26,928 --> 02:16:30,808
Do you know why you can never step
into the same river twice?

1645
02:16:33,060 --> 02:16:36,606
Yeah. 'Cause it's always moving.

1646
02:16:37,774 --> 02:16:41,612
I used to prepare
a pipe for my husband.

1647
02:16:48,036 --> 02:16:52,333
'Twas the morphine he took for
the wounds he suffered in his heart.

1648
02:16:55,670 --> 02:16:59,842
He would rage and he would cry,
my lost soldier.

1649
02:17:03,512 --> 02:17:07,434
And I said to him,
"There are two of you.

1650
02:17:07,559 --> 02:17:10,188
Don't you see?

1651
02:17:10,313 --> 02:17:14,192
One that kills
and one that loves."

1652
02:17:16,153 --> 02:17:18,322
And he said to me...

1653
02:17:18,447 --> 02:17:23,161
"I don't know whether
I'm an animal or a god."

1654
02:17:25,705 --> 02:17:27,583
But you are both.

1655
02:18:09,590 --> 02:18:11,467
You want more?

1656
02:18:16,890 --> 02:18:20,603
All that matters
is that you're alive.

1657
02:18:22,313 --> 02:18:25,066
You are alive, Captain.

1658
02:18:28,654 --> 02:18:30,906
That's the truth.

1659
02:19:44,034 --> 02:19:46,829
There are two of you,
don't you see?

1660
02:19:48,873 --> 02:19:51,376
One that kills...

1661
02:19:51,501 --> 02:19:53,838
and one that loves.

1662
02:20:22,413 --> 02:20:25,291
Can't see nothing.
We stoppin'.

1663
02:20:25,416 --> 02:20:27,961
You're not authorised
to stop this boat, Chief.

1664
02:20:28,086 --> 02:20:31,548
I said I can't see a thing, Captain.
I'm stopping this boat.

1665
02:20:31,673 --> 02:20:33,550
I ain't riskin'
no more lives.

1666
02:20:33,676 --> 02:20:36,387
I'm in command here, goddam it.
You'll do what I say.

1667
02:20:38,181 --> 02:20:40,058
You see anything, Chef?

1668
02:20:42,436 --> 02:20:45,189
Why don't they
fucking attack, man?

1669
02:21:03,711 --> 02:21:05,838
Watch it over here, Chief.

1670
02:21:06,797 --> 02:21:08,759
Got a stump.

1671
02:21:11,637 --> 02:21:13,347
On the fifties.

1672
02:21:13,472 --> 02:21:15,850
<i>He was close. </i>

1673
02:21:17,310 --> 02:21:19,437
<i>He was real close. </i>

1674
02:21:20,564 --> 02:21:24,026
<i>I couldn't see him yet,
but I could feel him... </i>

1675
02:21:24,151 --> 02:21:26,071
<i>as if the boat were being
sucked upriver... </i>

1676
02:21:26,196 --> 02:21:29,032
<i>and the water was
flowing back into the jungle. </i>

1677
02:21:31,576 --> 02:21:33,454
<i>Whatever was going to happen... </i>

1678
02:21:33,579 --> 02:21:37,458
<i>it wasn't going to be the way
they called it back in Nha Trang. </i>

1679
02:21:42,589 --> 02:21:44,968
- Arrows!
- Fire!

1680
02:21:47,303 --> 02:21:50,140
Chef, open up! Fire!

1681
02:21:53,352 --> 02:21:55,647
Lance, fire!

1682
02:22:03,364 --> 02:22:07,327
Chef! Chef, it's okay.
Quit firing.

1683
02:22:07,452 --> 02:22:11,081
- They're just little toy arrows.
- Cut it out! Quiet!

1684
02:22:11,206 --> 02:22:14,169
Chief, tell them
to hold their fire!

1685
02:22:14,294 --> 02:22:16,838
They're just little sticks.
They're just trying to scare us.

1686
02:22:16,963 --> 02:22:18,924
Quiet!

1687
02:22:19,049 --> 02:22:21,927
You got us into this mess,
and now you can't get us out...

1688
02:22:22,052 --> 02:22:24,514
because you don't know where
the hell you're going, do ya?

1689
02:22:24,639 --> 02:22:26,766
Do ya?

1690
02:22:26,892 --> 02:22:30,020
You son of a bitch!
You bastard!

1691
02:22:31,564 --> 02:22:33,816
Lance, get the wheel!

1692
02:22:33,941 --> 02:22:38,197
You savages! Come and get it!
You son of a bitches!

1693
02:22:58,470 --> 02:23:00,056
A spear?

1694
02:24:19,607 --> 02:24:22,736
My mission is to make it
up into Cambodia.

1695
02:24:22,861 --> 02:24:25,780
There's a Green Beret colonel
up there who's gone insane...

1696
02:24:25,906 --> 02:24:27,325
and I'm supposed to kill him.

1697
02:24:28,784 --> 02:24:31,704
That's fucking typical!
Shit!

1698
02:24:31,829 --> 02:24:34,082
Fuckin' Vietnam mission!

1699
02:24:34,208 --> 02:24:37,878
I'm short and we gotta go up there
so you can kill one of our own guys?

1700
02:24:38,003 --> 02:24:41,674
That's fucking great!
That's just fucking great, man.

1701
02:24:41,799 --> 02:24:45,971
Shit!
That's fuckin' crazy.

1702
02:24:46,055 --> 02:24:49,016
I mean, I thought you were
going in to blow up a bridge...

1703
02:24:49,141 --> 02:24:52,437
or some fuckin'
railroad tracks or somethin'.

1704
02:24:52,562 --> 02:24:54,981
- That's all right.
- No. No, wait. Wait.

1705
02:24:55,106 --> 02:24:58,444
We'll go together, on the boat.
We'll go with you.

1706
02:24:58,569 --> 02:25:02,991
We'll go up there,
but on the boat. Okay?

1707
02:26:09,068 --> 02:26:11,530
<i>Part of me was afraid
of what I would find... </i>

1708
02:26:11,655 --> 02:26:14,074
<i>and what I would do
when I got there. </i>

1709
02:26:16,035 --> 02:26:18,872
<i>I knew the risks... </i>

1710
02:26:18,997 --> 02:26:21,291
<i>or imagined I knew. </i>

1711
02:26:23,211 --> 02:26:25,755
<i>But the thing
I felt the most... </i>

1712
02:26:25,880 --> 02:26:28,967
<i>much stronger than fear... </i>

1713
02:26:29,092 --> 02:26:31,803
<i>was the desire to confront him. </i>

1714
02:27:43,637 --> 02:27:45,682
Just keep movin'.

1715
02:27:45,807 --> 02:27:49,936
Lance, keep your hands
away from the guns.

1716
02:29:16,746 --> 02:29:19,333
It's all right! It's all right!
It's all been approved!

1717
02:29:20,710 --> 02:29:23,755
I ain't comin' in there!
Them bastards attacked us!

1718
02:29:23,880 --> 02:29:28,343
Hey, zap 'em with your siren, man.
Zap 'em with your siren.

1719
02:29:38,564 --> 02:29:40,816
There's mines over there
and mines over there too.

1720
02:29:40,941 --> 02:29:44,112
And watch out. Those goddam
monkeys will bite you, I'll tell you.

1721
02:29:44,237 --> 02:29:47,450
Ah, that's a pretty one.
Move it right in towards me.

1722
02:29:47,575 --> 02:29:49,285
I'm an American.

1723
02:29:49,410 --> 02:29:52,204
Yeah. An American civilian.
Hi, Yanks.

1724
02:29:52,330 --> 02:29:54,791
Hi. American.

1725
02:29:54,917 --> 02:29:57,002
American civilian.
It's all right.

1726
02:29:57,127 --> 02:30:01,007
And you got the cigarettes. And that's
what I've been dreaming about.

1727
02:30:03,009 --> 02:30:05,763
- Who are you?
- Who are you?

1728
02:30:09,808 --> 02:30:11,436
I'm a photojournalist.

1729
02:30:11,561 --> 02:30:14,230
I've covered the war
since '64.

1730
02:30:14,356 --> 02:30:16,901
I've been in Laos,
Cambodia and 'Nam.

1731
02:30:20,279 --> 02:30:24,368
Hoo-wee, baby. I'll tell you one thing.
This boat is a mess, man.

1732
02:30:24,493 --> 02:30:26,745
Who are all these people?

1733
02:30:26,870 --> 02:30:30,667
Yeah, well, they think
you've come to...

1734
02:30:30,792 --> 02:30:32,085
to take him away.

1735
02:30:32,210 --> 02:30:35,381
- And I hope that isn't true.
- Take who away?

1736
02:30:37,549 --> 02:30:40,845
Him! Col. Kurtz.

1737
02:30:40,971 --> 02:30:44,683
These are all his children,
man, as far as you can see.

1738
02:30:44,808 --> 02:30:48,521
Hell, man, out here
we're all his children.

1739
02:30:48,646 --> 02:30:52,276
Could we talk to Col. Kurtz?

1740
02:30:52,401 --> 02:30:56,613
Hey, Mac.
You don't talk to the colonel.

1741
02:30:56,738 --> 02:30:58,616
Well, you listen to him.

1742
02:30:58,741 --> 02:31:01,995
The man's enlarged my mind.

1743
02:31:02,120 --> 02:31:05,791
He's a poet warrior
in the classic sense.

1744
02:31:05,916 --> 02:31:07,793
I mean, sometimes he'll...

1745
02:31:07,918 --> 02:31:09,504
Well, you say hello to him,
right?

1746
02:31:09,629 --> 02:31:12,007
He'll just walk by you
and he won't even notice you.

1747
02:31:12,132 --> 02:31:15,720
Then suddenly he'll grab you and he'll
throw you in a corner and he'll say...

1748
02:31:15,845 --> 02:31:17,847
"Do you know that 'if'
is the middle word in 'life'?

1749
02:31:17,972 --> 02:31:20,851
If you can keep your head when all about
you are losing theirs and blaming you.

1750
02:31:20,976 --> 02:31:23,270
If you can trust yourself
when all men doubt you."

1751
02:31:23,395 --> 02:31:26,482
I'm a little man. I'm a little man.
He's a great man.

1752
02:31:26,608 --> 02:31:29,736
"I should have been
a pair of ragged claws...

1753
02:31:29,861 --> 02:31:32,698
scuttling across floors
of silent seas."

1754
02:31:32,823 --> 02:31:35,034
- I mean...
- Stay with the boat.

1755
02:31:35,159 --> 02:31:39,581
Don't go any... Don't go without me,
okay? I wanna get a picture.

1756
02:31:41,374 --> 02:31:44,712
He can be terrible
and he can be mean...

1757
02:31:44,837 --> 02:31:46,714
and he can be right.

1758
02:31:46,839 --> 02:31:49,843
He's fighting the war.
He's a great man.

1759
02:31:53,263 --> 02:31:55,183
I mean...

1760
02:31:57,727 --> 02:32:01,231
I wish I had words, you know.
I wish I had words.

1761
02:32:01,357 --> 02:32:04,360
I could tell you something like,
the other day he wanted to kill me.

1762
02:32:04,485 --> 02:32:07,197
- Something like that.
- Why'd he want to kill you?

1763
02:32:07,322 --> 02:32:09,699
Because I took his picture.

1764
02:32:09,824 --> 02:32:13,371
He said, "If you take
my picture again...

1765
02:32:13,496 --> 02:32:16,040
I'm gonna kill you."

1766
02:32:16,123 --> 02:32:18,042
And he meant it.

1767
02:32:19,753 --> 02:32:22,422
See, just lay cool.
Lay cool.

1768
02:32:22,547 --> 02:32:24,467
Lay back. Dig it.

1769
02:32:24,592 --> 02:32:27,470
He gets friendly again.
He really does.

1770
02:32:27,595 --> 02:32:30,891
But you don't... you don't...
you don't judge the colonel.

1771
02:32:31,016 --> 02:32:33,686
You don't judge the colonel
like an ordinary man.

1772
02:32:40,485 --> 02:32:43,072
Okay, watch it now.
These are Americans. Americans!

1773
02:32:43,197 --> 02:32:46,033
You can feel the vibe
of this place.

1774
02:32:46,117 --> 02:32:49,496
Let me take your picture. Hey,
could you hold... Hey, hello. Hello.

1775
02:32:49,621 --> 02:32:51,540
Could you hold up
a minute?

1776
02:33:13,608 --> 02:33:14,984
Colby.

1777
02:33:31,128 --> 02:33:32,838
The heads.

1778
02:33:32,963 --> 02:33:35,133
You're looking at the heads.

1779
02:33:35,258 --> 02:33:38,428
I, uh... Sometimes
he goes too far.

1780
02:33:38,553 --> 02:33:41,265
He's the first one
to admit it.

1781
02:33:42,350 --> 02:33:45,269
- He's gone crazy.
- Wrong, wrong!

1782
02:33:46,605 --> 02:33:49,441
If you could have heard
the man just two days ago...

1783
02:33:49,566 --> 02:33:52,195
if you could have heard
him then, God...

1784
02:33:52,320 --> 02:33:55,573
- You were gonna call him crazy?
- Fuckin' A!

1785
02:33:57,701 --> 02:33:59,995
I just wanna talk to him.

1786
02:34:01,372 --> 02:34:04,626
Well, man, he's gone away.

1787
02:34:04,751 --> 02:34:07,462
He's gone away. He disappeared
out in the jungle with his people.

1788
02:34:07,587 --> 02:34:10,675
- I'll wait for him.
- He feels comfortable with his people.

1789
02:34:10,800 --> 02:34:13,678
He forgets himself
with his people.

1790
02:34:15,055 --> 02:34:17,808
- He forgets himself.
- Captain?

1791
02:34:17,933 --> 02:34:20,937
Maybe we should wait
back at the boat.

1792
02:34:21,062 --> 02:34:22,522
- I think you should...
- Okay, Chef.

1793
02:34:22,647 --> 02:34:24,857
We'll go back to the boat
for a while.

1794
02:34:24,983 --> 02:34:27,695
Yeah, stay with Lance.

1795
02:34:50,722 --> 02:34:53,474
This colonel guy,
he's wacko, man.

1796
02:34:53,599 --> 02:34:56,145
He's worse than crazy.
He's evil!

1797
02:34:56,270 --> 02:34:58,647
I mean, that's what the man's got
set up here, man!

1798
02:34:58,772 --> 02:35:01,233
It's fuckin' pagan idolatry.
Look around you!

1799
02:35:02,277 --> 02:35:05,488
- Shit, he's loco.
- Then you'll help me?

1800
02:35:05,613 --> 02:35:08,659
Fuckin' A, I'll help you. I'll do
anything to get out of this joint.

1801
02:35:08,784 --> 02:35:11,996
- Good boy.
- We could blow all them assholes away.

1802
02:35:12,121 --> 02:35:15,917
They're so fuckin' spaced out,
they wouldn't even know it.

1803
02:35:16,043 --> 02:35:20,673
I ain't afraid of all them
fuckin' skulls and altars and shit.

1804
02:35:22,300 --> 02:35:26,180
I used to think if I died
in an evil place...

1805
02:35:26,305 --> 02:35:29,516
then my soul wouldn't be able
to make it to Heaven.

1806
02:35:29,642 --> 02:35:32,854
But now, fuck...

1807
02:35:34,439 --> 02:35:37,360
I mean, I don't care where it goes,
as long as it ain't here.

1808
02:35:37,485 --> 02:35:41,280
So what do you wanna do?
I'll kill the fuck.

1809
02:35:41,405 --> 02:35:44,326
- Get out of here.
- I'm gonna need you to wait here, Chef.

1810
02:35:44,451 --> 02:35:48,748
I'll go up with Lance and
scrounge around, check the place out.

1811
02:35:48,873 --> 02:35:51,292
See if I can find
the colonel, okay?

1812
02:35:52,627 --> 02:35:55,631
Well, what do you
want me to do?

1813
02:35:55,756 --> 02:35:58,884
Here. You take the radio...

1814
02:35:59,009 --> 02:36:03,306
and if I don't get back
by 2200 hours...

1815
02:36:04,849 --> 02:36:07,478
you call in the air strike.

1816
02:36:08,854 --> 02:36:11,566
"Air strike?"

1817
02:36:11,692 --> 02:36:13,568
The code is "Almighty"...

1818
02:36:13,694 --> 02:36:17,072
coordinates zero-niner-two-six-
four-seven-one-two.

1819
02:36:17,197 --> 02:36:19,367
It's all in there.

1820
02:36:20,910 --> 02:36:24,915
Zero-niner-two-six-
four-seven-one-two.

1821
02:36:32,215 --> 02:36:36,178
<i>Everything I saw told me
that Kurtz had gone insane. </i>

1822
02:36:39,849 --> 02:36:41,893
<i>The place was full of bodies... </i>

1823
02:36:42,019 --> 02:36:46,189
<i>North Vietnamese,
Vietcong, Cambodians. </i>

1824
02:36:53,240 --> 02:36:57,578
<i>If I was still alive,
it was because he wanted me that way. </i>

1825
02:37:30,784 --> 02:37:34,497
<i>It smelled like
slow death in there... </i>

1826
02:37:34,622 --> 02:37:36,916
<i>malaria... </i>

1827
02:37:37,041 --> 02:37:38,919
